</div>

    </div>
  </div>
    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4348846654" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4348846654" />
    <a title="Airin Efferin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/127133601-airin-efferin"><img alt="Airin Efferin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611307300p2/127133601.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4348846654?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Airin Efferin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Airin Efferin" href="/user/show/127133601-airin-efferin">Airin Efferin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4348846654" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11832270710595556489">I&apos;m not a professional economist, nor historian, nor finance person, I&apos;m just someone who is curious about many things, generally reads middle-grade, YA fantasy, and erotica SO what am I doing reading this book?<br/><br/>Well I started it last year (2020) when the pandemic hit and we found ourselves in an economic crisis as well as a health crisis, and I thought hey why not make myself feel better by reading a book about other humans who also went through economic crises! We&apos;re not alone right! <br/><br/>I had to p</span>
  <span id="freeText11832270710595556489" style="display:none">I'm not a professional economist, nor historian, nor finance person, I'm just someone who is curious about many things, generally reads middle-grade, YA fantasy, and erotica SO what am I doing reading this book?<br /><br />Well I started it last year (2020) when the pandemic hit and we found ourselves in an economic crisis as well as a health crisis, and I thought hey why not make myself feel better by reading a book about other humans who also went through economic crises! We're not alone right! <br /><br />I had to put it down because like I said I usually read stuff about fairies and magic and hot steamy sex. But occasionally I get this compulsion to try to make my brain a little smarter and so I made myself pick up this book again this year.<br /><br />There were some insights I learned about money and our financial systems, so my purposes were satisfied. Some went way over my head, and I probably retained like 1% of the whole book, which I'm quite proud of actually. Here are some insights that I retained:<br /><br />1. Insurance was invented in Scotland, originally to help protect widows and kids of ministers who died before they were supposed to die. <br /><br />2. The author agreed that women are more creditworthy than men (I should give him 5 stars just for this)<br /><br />3. Property is not risk-free investment and was a political move to make humans feel this way. Hurrah again to this. I never understood why people of my parents' generation just kept buying houses and land. I never even understood how humans can even "own land." I always think that the land owns us, rather than us owning it. <br /><br />4. There is always going to be another crisis (Hello, I picked this book up in the middle of one). There is no one future, there are just multiple possible futures that will always surprise us (Yeah so let's have a drink and just be happy while we can? Resiliency is key? Take it a day at a time?)<br /><br />Too bad the author didn't go into cryptocurrency because that's all the rage now in 2021. <br /><br />Okay that's it, cheers. Stay healthy, stay alive, have money.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11832270710595556489" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

